<paragraph blockId="26.[264,1323,1595,1891]" lastBlockId="27.[360,1322,290,372]" lastPageId="27" lastPageNumber="28" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,376,1867,1891]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<typeStatus box="[312,376,1867,1891]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Types</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
: The 
<typeStatus box="[445,539,1867,1890]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">syntypes</typeStatus>
in 
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34991" box="[577,659,1867,1890]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34991" name="Hungarian Natural History Museum (Termeszettudomanyi Muzeum)" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">HNHM</collectionCode>
were destroyed in 
<number box="[871,928,1867,1890]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="1956.0">1956</number>
. Two 
<typeStatus box="[996,1079,1867,1890]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">syntype</typeStatus>
males in Bezzi’s own collection in 
<collectionCode box="[505,586,290,313]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">MSNM</collectionCode>
are in good condition but the one captured on 
<date box="[1114,1214,290,313]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="1906-11-05">
<number box="[1114,1127,290,313]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="5.0">5</number>
.xi. 
<number box="[1156,1214,290,313]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="1906.0">1906</number>
</date>
lacks the right middle leg. Consequently, the other male collected on 
<date box="[1006,1119,319,342]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="1906-11-20">
<number box="[1006,1035,319,342]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="20.0">20</number>
.xi. 
<number box="[1063,1119,319,342]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="1906.0">1906</number>
</date>
is here selected as 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[360,462,348,372]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<typeStatus box="[360,462,348,372]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">lectotype</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[477,557,349,372]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 – 16" captionStartId="22.[264,383,290,314]" captionText="FIGURES 11 – 16. Lectotype specimens of species of Bombyliidae referred to in Bezzi’s manuscript. 11, Bombylius phaeopterus Bezzi, male habitus (lectotype in BMNH). 12, Bombylius fucatus Bezzi [= Parisus], male habitus (lectotype in MSNM). 13, Pantostomus gibbiventris Bezzi, female habitus (lectotype in MSNM). 14, Tomomyza barbatula Bezzi, male habitus (lectotype in MSNM). 15 – 16, Tomomyza pallipes Bezzi (lectotype in MSNM). 15, male habitus. 16, wing." pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
Fig. 
<number box="[527,557,349,372]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="14.0">14</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
